# 02 Code Rules

## Architecture goals
Build the app like a production internal enterprise system.
The codebase should be modular, easy to extend, and easy for Cursor to modify safely.

Prefer a clean separation between:
- UI components
- feature modules
- state and data access
- agent logic
- mock data
- business rules
- utilities

## Recommended stack
Use a modern React stack with TypeScript.
Preferred choices:
- React with a component-based architecture
- Next.js or a similarly structured React framework
- TypeScript everywhere
- Tailwind or a similar utility-based styling approach
- reusable UI primitives
- mock service layer for data and AI behavior

Do not tightly couple the app to a specific backend unless required.
The initial experience should work with mock data and local agent simulation.

## File organization
Keep code organized by feature and responsibility.
Suggested structure:
- src/components
- src/features
- src/pages or src/app
- src/services
- src/agents
- src/mock
- src/types
- src/utils
- src/hooks
- src/contexts
- src/constants

Do not place all logic inside page files.
Do not put agent logic in components.
Do not put mock data inside JSX files.

## Component rules
All components should be:
- small
- reusable
- composable
- typed
- easy to test

Avoid giant page components that include business logic, data shaping, and rendering in one file.
Split complex pages into:
- header sections
- summary cards
- tables
- side panels
- drawers
- filters
- action bars
- status components

## Design system rules
Create shared primitives before building screens.
At minimum support components for:
- Button
- Card
- Badge
- Table
- Drawer
- Modal
- Tabs
- Input
- Select
- Textarea
- Search field
- Metric card
- Timeline
- Progress bar
- Empty state
- Comment block
- Activity item
- Agent insight card
- Recommendation card
- Email composer
- Status chip

If a UI pattern repeats twice, extract it into a reusable component.

## State management rules
Use a predictable state model.
Source of truth should come from mock data services or a centralized store.
Avoid hidden local state that creates inconsistent screens.

Recommended state categories:
- workflow records
- selected entity
- filters
- UI visibility state
- agent responses
- activity feed
- form state
- asynchronous loading/error state

Status changes must flow through explicit update functions.
Do not mutate records in arbitrary places.

## Data modeling rules
Use explicit types or interfaces for every important entity.
At minimum define types for:
- Category
- ItemType
- AssortmentPlan
- Lead
- SellerProfile
- Application
- Partner
- OnboardingTask
- ActivityEvent
- EmailDraft
- BeaconRecommendation
- AgentRun

Keep the same ID values across related entities.
Do not generate unrelated duplicate records unless the product needs them.

## Data access rules
All application data should come from structured mock sources or a mock service layer.
The UI should not depend on hardcoded inline arrays unless the data is tiny and local to one component.

Use service functions such as:
- getAssortmentPlans
- getLeads
- getPartnerById
- updateLeadStatus
- createEmailDraft
- submitApplication
- startOnboarding
- completeTask
- runBeaconAgent

The exact function names can vary, but the architecture should stay service oriented.

## Mock data rules
Mock data must feel realistic and internally consistent.
Use believable combinations of:
- seller names
- categories
- GMV values
- marketplace presence
- ratings
- confidence scores
- onboarding tasks
- communication history

Mock data should support all major screens and business states.
Do not create a dataset that only works for one page.

## Workflow logic rules
Implement workflow changes as explicit actions.
Each action should update the canonical lifecycle state and create an activity event.

Examples:
- shortlistLead()
- sendOutreachEmail()
- submitSellerApplication()
- beginReview()
- approvePartner()
- rejectPartner()
- markFutureInterest()
- startOnboardingTask()
- completeOnboardingTask()

Do not let random UI clicks alter the business state without a controlled action.

## Business logic rules
Do not encode business rules directly inside JSX.
Business logic should live in:
- services
- reducers
- state machines
- hooks
- utility functions
- agent modules

If a rule is important enough to explain to a user, it is important enough to live outside the view layer.

## Status and review model
Use two separate fields when relevant:
- lifecycle status
- review outcome

Do not collapse them into one ambiguous field if the data model needs both.

## Rendering rules
The UI should render from state.
Avoid manual DOM manipulation.
Avoid duplicated conditional blocks when a status configuration map can be used instead.

Prefer configuration objects for:
- status labels
- colors
- next actions
- empty states
- step descriptions
- recommended prompts

## Table and list rules
The app will rely heavily on tables and list views.
Tables should support:
- sorting
- filtering
- search
- pagination or virtualization if needed
- row actions
- row click to open detail view
- status badges
- contextual summary columns

List rows should be informative, not cluttered.
Keep the most important business signals visible.

## Detail view rules
Use a drawer or side panel for deep details when appropriate.
The detail view should show:
- entity summary
- status
- key metrics
- activity timeline
- comments
- AI insight
- next actions

Avoid forcing a full page navigation when a drawer is enough.

## Form rules
Use controlled or well-managed forms.
Validate forms clearly.
Return human-readable error messages.
Do not hide validation failures.

Forms relevant to this product include:
- seller application review
- email drafts
- onboarding tasks
- assortment plan inputs
- search and filtering controls

## Error handling rules
Handle loading, empty, and error states explicitly.
Never leave a dead end.
Every error should say what happened and how the user can recover.

## Performance rules
Keep the app responsive.
Avoid unnecessary rerenders.
Memoize expensive derived data if needed.
Do not compute complex summaries repeatedly inside render functions if they can be derived once.

## Accessibility rules
Use semantic HTML wherever possible.
Buttons must be buttons.
Inputs must have labels.
Status text should be readable without color alone.
Ensure keyboard accessibility for drawers, modals, tabs, and tables.

## Naming rules
Use clear business names.
Prefer Target Plus terminology over generic placeholders.
Examples:
- lead instead of record when the page is about discovery
- partner instead of generic user when the record is an approved seller
- onboarding task instead of generic todo
- assortment plan instead of generic plan

Use consistent naming across files, types, and UI labels.

## API and service rules
Even if the app is mock-first, design the code as if APIs exist.
Use typed service boundaries and predictable response shapes.
Return structured objects rather than raw strings whenever possible.

## Asynchronous behavior rules
AI calls and data updates should show:
- loading state
- success state
- error state
- final state update

Never pretend asynchronous work is instant unless the UI specifically models it that way.

## Commenting rules
Comment only where the logic is not obvious.
Do not comment on every line.
Use comments to explain business meaning, agent behavior, or tricky state transitions.

## Testing mindset
Even if tests are not implemented immediately, code should be written so that it could be tested easily.
Prefer pure functions for:
- status transitions
- ranking logic
- recommendation generation
- formatting utilities
- data transforms

## Module boundaries
Keep modules responsible for one thing.
Examples:
- discovery module
- onboarding module
- assortment module
- beacon module
- mock data module
- activity module

Do not create circular dependencies between features.

## Seed data rules
Seed data should power the demo story.
At least support these user journeys:
- a seller is discovered and shortlisted
- the lead is contacted
- the application is submitted
- the partner enters review
- the partner is approved
- onboarding starts
- onboarding completes
- another seller is rejected or marked future interest

## Implementation order
Build in this order:
1. application shell
2. shared design system
3. mock data layer
4. assortment planning screens
5. lead discovery screens
6. potential partner review screens
7. onboarding screens
8. activity and comments
9. Beacon UI
10. agent integration

## Final code quality standard
The app should feel maintainable by a real team.
When in doubt, choose code that is:
- explicit
- typed
- modular
- state driven
- easy to extend
- aligned to the business workflow
